liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Brazilian Navy says it seized 3.6 metric tons of cocaine on a boat off the coast of Brazil's northeastern Pernambuco state. That's almost the equivalent weight of two cars ! In a statement, the Navy said it had captured a small motor boat used for transporting people and cargo along the coast with five crew members heading to Africa. It comes after a series of operations held by the Navy to fight drug transportation on the country's coast. According to the Navy, over 17 tons of cocaine have been seized since 2020. That's about as heavy as nine-and-a-half cars ...but if you prefer animal weight comparisons, that's about 20 cows.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Brazil's Navy seizes record quantity of cocaine nearly twice as heavy as a car

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A new survey has found two-thirds of Australians who attend arts events and festivals are doing so less frequently. The 2022 National Arts Participation Survey asked some 10,000 people about their engagement with the sector. The results show 68 per cent of the population aged 15 or over attend live events such as concerts, theatre or festivals. That's the same figure as before COVID-19, allaying fears people may have disengaged since the last survey in 2019. But people are attending less frequently, going every few months rather than each week. The cost of living may be biting — about half of those who attend live arts want to go more often, but cost and distance are holding them back. Ticket prices are one barrier for people and two in five Australians say there are no arts events near where they live. It all shows access to free or low-cost arts events should be a priority, according to new national arts funding body Creative Australia, which runs the survey.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Aussies seeing fewer live shows as ticket prices bite

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: More than 1,200 bank branches have shut down in the past six years – with more expected until 2026 – as the nation’s banks slowly phase out Australian consumers’ access to cash. Regional communities have been disproportionately affected by these branch closures. The bosses of major banks will be questioned in a Senate inquiry about the future of regional banking. The Senate will be hearing from representatives form Commonwealth Bank, Westpac and NAB this morning followed by ANZ this afternoon.
